# Quote / Eval: homoiconic .O

This example demonstrates \quote^(...)_quote and `O.eval(expr)`: the pair of
operators that make .O homoiconic across languages. `quote^` captures its
body as an unevaluated `OExpr` value; `O.eval` re-enters the evaluator on
one.

## A quoted expression is a value

python[0]^(
q = quote^(python^(6 * 7)_python)_quote
type(q).__name__   # the value the Markdown backend will render
)_python[0]

The quoted form is opaque until we evaluate it:

python[0]^(
O.eval(q)          # -> 42
)_python[0]

## Building O code in Python

Because `quote^` returns a Python-visible `OExpr`, we can collect several of
them in a list and evaluate them conditionally:

python[0]^(
variants = [
  quote^(python^(sum(range(10)))_python)_quote,
  quote^(python^(len("structural realism"))_python)_quote,
  quote^(python^(2 ** 10)_python)_quote,
]
results = [O.eval(v) for v in variants]
results
)_python[0]

## Quote + splicing for metaprogramming

The same machinery works the other way -- Python can CONSTRUCT a .O source
string and quote it:

python[0]^(
src = "\python^(111 + 222)_python"     # backslash escapes the inner opener
O.eval(O.quote(src))
)_python[0]

## Explicit lexical scope

The one-argument form captures the scope at the callback site. The two-argument
form accepts an OScope value, so the chosen namespace is explicit:

python[0]^(
captured = O.scope({"answer": 41})
scoped = quote^(python[1]^($answer + 1)_python[1])_quote
O.eval(scoped, captured)  # -> 42
)_python[0]

## Why this matters

Lisp's power famously derives from code-as-data: a program can produce the
text of another program and hand it to the same evaluator. .O generalizes
that across arbitrary target languages. A single expression tree is now a
fix-point of parse, quote, splice, and eval -- the grammar of programs, not
the grammar of a particular language.
)_markdown
)_O
